87
00:06:31,434 --> 00:06:36,756
to begin to open up or to really manifest and make sort of visible

88
00:06:37,136 --> 00:06:40,137
what is so fascinating and unique about video game design.

89
00:06:41,097 --> 00:06:47,942
And so in the very early stages of the exhibition, I worked a lot to try and find a core quote or concept or an idea

90
00:06:48,362 --> 00:06:55,087
that to me got to the sort of fundamental aspects of what makes video games such a unique and fascinating discipline.

91
00:06:55,892 --> 00:07:00,137
And I came across this quote which was a line from Frank Lantz's talk Hearts and Minds,

92
00:07:00,157 --> 00:07:03,080
which is a really great talk from GDC that he presented in 2014.

93
00:07:03,541 --> 00:07:05,983
And this is a quote that says,

94
00:07:06,484 --> 00:07:09,948
Making games combines everything that's hard about building a bridge

95
00:07:10,368 --> 00:07:12,831
and everything that's hard about composing an opera.

96
00:07:13,392 --> 00:07:15,514
Games are operas made out of bridges.

97
00:07:15,995 --> 00:07:18,298
This is a really confident and bombastic statement.

98
00:07:18,618 --> 00:07:22,704
Here we're aligning video games with the sort of cultural heights of operas

99
00:07:22,764 --> 00:07:27,610
and with equally forms such as these essential forms such as engineering.

100
00:07:28,291 --> 00:07:30,835
But for me, not just that confidence in this statement,

101
00:07:30,875 --> 00:07:34,019
but also the fact that this is a statement that allows us to view video games.

102
00:07:34,680 --> 00:07:41,106
As this system, this sort of cultural form that sort of embodies this subjective emotional aesthetic design,

103
00:07:41,247 --> 00:07:46,552
but also this objective system design of systems of engineering of rules.

104
00:07:47,013 --> 00:07:50,036
And there is a fascinating tension where those two points meet.

105
00:07:50,516 --> 00:07:54,180
And for me, that is what we wanted to get to the heart of in this exhibition.

106
00:07:54,540 --> 00:07:58,103
to evoke and instill in people what is so important and unique.

107
00:07:58,143 --> 00:08:02,266
And equally for me, this space, when we were able to reduce video games

108
00:08:02,326 --> 00:08:04,867
to sort of the fundamentals or to their basics,

109
00:08:05,308 --> 00:08:08,630
I think it gives us a little bit of breathing space to understand

110
00:08:08,710 --> 00:08:12,532
or to perhaps envisage much broader horizons about the discipline.

111
00:08:12,892 --> 00:08:16,215
It allows us to cast off some of the assumptions, the stereotypes,

112
00:08:16,915 --> 00:08:20,377
or some of the hang-ups that perhaps sometimes sort of overshadow the discipline.

113
00:08:21,218 --> 00:08:24,762
And so this is the first quote that people come to when they come to the exhibition,

114
00:08:24,782 --> 00:08:26,625
when they first see when they come into the exhibition.

115
00:08:27,686 --> 00:08:31,611
So it's an exhibition that was seeking to really challenge people's expectations.

116
00:08:32,031 --> 00:08:34,014
This is an exhibition that sought to take risks.

117
00:08:35,085 --> 00:08:41,470
And for one, this is a show which was deciding to not look back over nostalgic, retro past.

118
00:08:41,550 --> 00:08:43,872
Instead, we're looking at video games from the here and now.

119
00:08:44,332 --> 00:08:47,755
We're looking at a period of time from the mid-2000s through to the present day.

120
00:08:48,135 --> 00:08:52,599
The reason why we decided on that specific time frame is that, sort of, within the mid-2000s,

121
00:08:52,619 --> 00:08:57,863
we have a whole host of technological catalysts, from smartphone to broadband to social media,

122
00:08:58,623 --> 00:09:02,146
all of which have had a radical, radical impact on the way that games are designed,

123
00:09:02,246 --> 00:09:04,388
the way that they're discussed, and the way that they're played.

124
00:09:05,852 --> 00:09:10,739
Equally, this was an exhibition that was trying to find a new curatorial language for video games.

125
00:09:11,180 --> 00:09:14,564
We wanted to look beyond video games purely as a playable object,

126
00:09:14,604 --> 00:09:20,413
to find new ways of opening up and making visible this as a fascinating design medium.

127
00:09:22,523 --> 00:09:42,362
And one of the things that is particularly surprising is that one of the first objects that was ever confirmed as alone for the exhibition was in fact a painting, this Magritte painting that you can see, the blank signature, which formed sort of a key inspirational touch point for this scene in Carble Computer's game Kentucky Route Zero.

128
00:09:43,263 --> 00:09:51,867
And for me, this is something that speaks to what is so intrinsically valuable about bringing video games into spaces such as museums.

129
00:09:52,187 --> 00:09:58,570
It is not to say that aligning video games alongside painting, alongside these established artistic masters,

130
00:09:59,090 --> 00:10:04,953
it's not to say, great, now video games are elevated to some lofty sort of space, now these are culture, now this is art.

131
00:10:05,673 --> 00:10:09,175
Instead, it's to show how video games, as a contemporary discipline,

132
00:10:09,675 --> 00:10:13,477
it does not sit as some sort of isolated cultural design discipline.

133
00:10:13,537 --> 00:10:18,359
It is intricately connected to this long history of visual arts,

134
00:10:18,399 --> 00:10:23,041
of literature, of culture, that it is a continuation of the subjects,

135
00:10:23,081 --> 00:10:26,903
and the mediums, and the disciplines that sit within the spaces such as the V&A.

