141
00:11:57,759 --> 00:12:03,102
So as I said just shortly before, this was an exhibition that was seeking to identify

142
00:12:03,122 --> 00:12:06,003
and find a new curatorial language for video games.

143
00:12:06,723 --> 00:12:11,445
And for that we wanted to look beyond the game as a playable object, to decentralise

144
00:12:11,465 --> 00:12:12,966
that as an object for an exhibition.

145
00:12:13,887 --> 00:12:19,230
Because bringing video games into museum spaces and exhibiting it is a complex, complex thing

146
00:12:19,310 --> 00:12:19,650
to do.

147
00:12:20,191 --> 00:12:23,573
Because inherently, we're trying to fit a square peg into a round hole.

148
00:12:24,093 --> 00:12:28,916
We're bringing video games, a medium that is plural, a medium that is ephemeral, a medium

149
00:12:28,956 --> 00:12:35,039
that is digital, into an institution whose entire structures and infrastructure is centered

150
00:12:35,079 --> 00:12:39,982
around valuing the sort of physical object, around sort of objects that exist sort of

151
00:12:40,062 --> 00:12:42,403
materially, that have this sort of singularity.

152
00:12:43,444 --> 00:12:50,280
And through that we have this sort of conflict of the way in which we can perhaps sort of view a game in that space.

153
00:12:51,316 --> 00:13:03,179
And playable games in terms of an exhibition space, it's not to say that I completely sort of disagree with the idea of bringing a game as a playable work into an exhibition as being the best means to display it, but it's really a question of context.

154
00:13:03,559 --> 00:13:07,220
This is an exhibition that wanted to open up video games as a design object.

155
00:13:07,960 --> 00:13:20,743
And so say if we bring a video game into that space, an object that might take upwards of 30 hours for you to play it before you can really realize or see that as a design object, do you as a visitor have time to have that engagement with that work?

156
00:13:21,523 --> 00:13:22,843
Equally, we have issues of capacity.

157
00:13:22,923 --> 00:13:25,484
How many people can play a video game in a public space?

158
00:13:26,385 --> 00:13:28,205
We also have issues of literacy.

159
00:13:28,585 --> 00:13:32,346
Who comes in with the skills and the knowledge of how to play and interact with a video game

160
00:13:32,366 --> 00:13:35,908
in order to be able to perceive it or experience it as a design object?

161
00:13:36,208 --> 00:13:40,509
And that's equally to speak of the fear of performance within a public space, that people

162
00:13:40,549 --> 00:13:43,390
feel that pressure of performing or playing a video game in public.

163
00:13:44,476 --> 00:13:49,726
So if we're not looking at the video game as the sort of key object and we want to find

164
00:13:49,767 --> 00:13:51,851
a new curatorial language, what does that look like?

165
00:13:51,891 --> 00:13:52,773
How do we approach this?

166
00:13:53,875 --> 00:13:59,298
And this way sort of comes back to looking at sort of other areas and other disciplines

167
00:13:59,318 --> 00:14:04,741
