Redemption or L.A. Noire.

175
00:14:31,900 --> 00:14:36,505
And what you're watching is the artist playing these games in this very intentional and considered

176
00:14:36,545 --> 00:14:37,806
way that's very choreographed.

177
00:14:37,866 --> 00:14:39,526
but almost seemingly a little bit irrational.

178
00:14:40,267 --> 00:14:44,227
In his playthroughs, he's sometimes repeatedly pushing NPCs

179
00:14:44,267 --> 00:14:47,108
to sort of push their behavior to respond in a different way.

180
00:14:47,148 --> 00:14:49,229
He's repeatedly sort of approaching them

181
00:14:49,269 --> 00:14:50,409
and sort of pushing their behaviors.

182
00:14:50,469 --> 00:14:52,629
Or he's sometimes going through games

183
00:14:52,689 --> 00:14:54,770
with a thick sort of specific path

184
00:14:54,790 --> 00:14:57,411
that he wants to travel through sort of any one landscape,

185
00:14:57,491 --> 00:15:00,111
but frequently coming up against the invisible walls

186
00:15:00,151 --> 00:15:02,872
or barriers that sort of are in place in that game

187
00:15:02,912 --> 00:15:06,233
to sort of direct or divert sort of players into other areas.

188
00:15:07,180 --> 00:15:09,500
And by watching these playthroughs, by watching this, Timmy,

189
00:15:10,280 --> 00:15:11,161
it begins to...

190
00:15:11,521 --> 00:15:15,001
You begin to see, as a person watching this artwork,

191
00:15:15,021 --> 00:15:17,582
you begin to see the seams in these video games.

192
00:15:17,622 --> 00:15:19,482
You begin to perceive the materiality.

193
00:15:19,862 --> 00:15:22,683
You begin to see sort of the considerations and the decisions

194
00:15:22,703 --> 00:15:24,163
that the designers have had to have made

195
00:15:24,544 --> 00:15:25,844
to be able to create those works.

196
00:15:26,284 --> 00:15:27,604
And this installation, for me,

197
00:15:28,384 --> 00:15:31,945
is perhaps one of the most inspirational installations I've seen

198
00:15:31,985 --> 00:15:35,506
because it has explained to me or presented to me...

199
00:15:35,926 --> 00:15:41,915
A video game as a designed object in an exhibition space far greater than actually any exhibition

200
00:15:41,935 --> 00:15:46,000
that I'd been to that actually tried to do so through the playable works.

201
00:15:46,951 --> 00:15:51,592
And so again, it's looking at spaces or concepts like this of how we can consider curation.

202
00:15:51,632 --> 00:15:55,633
And I think for me as a curator, that is really where my provocation starts from.

203
00:15:55,653 --> 00:15:59,635
That's where my practice is centred at the moment, is understanding that you as a curator

204
00:15:59,675 --> 00:16:03,236
take on the responsibility or the role of a player.

205
00:16:03,296 --> 00:16:07,777
That it is your responsibility to look at a video game, to identify what playthrough,

206
00:16:07,837 --> 00:16:11,298
what way or what lens do I want you to understand or appreciate this work.

207
00:16:13,428 --> 00:16:20,232
